  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Once you exchange contracts on a Queensland property, there is a period between exchange and settlement where the property is under contract but has not yet legally changed hands. For most Brisbane sellers, this gap runs somewhere between 30 and 90 days. During that window, you are still the legal owner and, under Queensland law, you still bear the risk. If something goes wrong with the property in that period, the obligation to make it right sits with you, not the buyer.</p>

      <p>This surprises many sellers. The assumption is often that once a buyer has signed and the deposit is paid, any damage is the buyer's problem. In Queensland, that is not how the law works. Risk passes at settlement, not at exchange. It is one of the more important distinctions between Queensland and some other states, and not knowing it can leave sellers in a genuinely difficult position.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the Queensland rule means in practice</h2>

      <p>If your property is damaged between exchange and settlement by fire, flood, storm, vandalism, or any other cause, you as the seller are responsible for making good that damage. The buyer purchased the property as it was on the date of exchange. You are obligated to deliver it in that condition, or as close to it as circumstances allow, on settlement day.</p>

      <p>The buyer's options when damage occurs are not unlimited. They can require you to repair the damage before settlement. They can negotiate a price reduction that reflects the damage. Or, in cases where the damage is severe enough that the property is materially different from what they contracted to buy, they may have grounds to terminate the contract. None of these are comfortable outcomes for a seller who is mid-move and expecting a clean settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Your obligations when damage occurs</h2>

      <p>The moment you become aware of damage to the property after exchange, there are four things you need to do promptly. Notify your insurer and make a claim. Photograph everything before any repairs or cleanup begin. Notify the buyer's agent and the buyer's solicitor in writing. Get repair quotes so you understand the scope and cost of what needs to be fixed.</p>

      <p>Transparency with the buyer is not optional. The buyer has a right to know the property has been damaged, and attempting to proceed to settlement without disclosure can expose you to serious legal consequences. Your own solicitor should be your first call after the insurer. They will guide you on how to manage the disclosure and any renegotiation with the buyer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why insurance to settlement is essential</h2>

      <p>Building insurance must be maintained right through to settlement. This is not a technicality. It is the mechanism that protects you in exactly the scenario described above. If a storm causes significant roof damage a week before settlement and you have no building insurance in place, you are exposed to the full repair cost out of pocket while also managing an agitated buyer and a settlement that may not proceed.</p>

      <p>The insurance claim covers the cost of repairs. What sellers sometimes underestimate is that if there is a shortfall between the insured amount and the actual repair cost, the seller bears that difference. Underinsurance, particularly in older Brisbane properties where rebuild costs have risen significantly in recent years, is a real risk. Check that your sum insured reflects the current cost of rebuilding the property, not just its market value.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Special conditions in the contract</h2>

      <p>Some contracts include a special condition specifying how damage between exchange and settlement is handled. These conditions vary in their terms and in how they affect the default Queensland position. Before you sign, read any special conditions with your solicitor. Understanding what a particular contract says about risk allocation, repair obligations, and the buyer's rights if damage occurs is far better done at the start of the contract than in the middle of a crisis.</p>

      <p>In some cases, a well-drafted special condition can provide sellers with more certainty about how a damage event would be resolved. In other cases, a condition inserted by a buyer's solicitor may go further than the default position. Know what you have agreed to before exchange, not after.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The vacant property risk</h2>

      <p>Sellers who move out of the property before settlement need to be particularly careful. An unoccupied property is at significantly higher risk of damage from a range of causes, including storm damage that is not quickly identified, water leaks from plumbing, and in some areas, vandalism or break-ins. If the property is vacant for any period before settlement, notify your insurer immediately. Many home and contents policies have conditions around vacancy periods, and an undisclosed vacancy can affect a claim.</p>

      <p>Arrange for someone to check the property regularly, particularly after significant weather events. A brief inspection every week or two is a reasonable precaution and can catch minor issues before they become major ones. If you have a property manager or a trusted neighbour who can do a visual check after a storm, use them.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should take away from this</h2>

      <p>The period between exchange and settlement is not a passive one for Brisbane sellers. You remain responsible for the property's condition and you carry real risk during that time. The combination of current building insurance, an accurate sum insured, and prompt action if anything goes wrong gives you the best protection. Your solicitor and your insurer are the two contacts you need to have ready.</p>

      <p>If you are moving out before settlement, be especially deliberate about insurance notification and property checks. The cost of a brief inspection is negligible compared to arriving at settlement day with an unresolved damage dispute.</p>

